# ADR-0007 — Serialize Browser Automation Execution

> Status: Accepted
>
> Date: 2026-07-13

---

# Context

Browser automations interact with external web applications using Playwright.

The current framework reuses a persistent authenticated browser session to avoid repeated logins and improve performance.

Simultaneous browser automations may interfere with each other by sharing:

- browser storage state;
- authentication cookies;
- downloaded files;
- external platform state.

The expected workload for the first production deployment is low, typically one automation request at a time.

---

# Decision

Serialize browser automation execution within the API process.

Before any browser automation starts, the framework acquires a global automation lock.

If another automation is already running:

```
409 Conflict
```

is returned immediately.

The request is not queued.

The browser is never started.

---

# Architecture

```
HTTP Request

↓

Bearer Authentication

↓

Automation Lock

↓

BrowserManager

↓

Playwright

↓

Dinantia

↓

HTTP Response

↓

Release Lock
```

The lock is implemented inside the API layer and remains transparent to the rest of the framework.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- Prevents concurrent use of the same browser session.
- Eliminates download directory collisions.
- Simplifies browser lifecycle management.
- Reduces operational complexity.
- Keeps browser behaviour deterministic.
- Avoids race conditions inside external platforms.

Negative:

- Only one automation may execute at a time.
- Additional requests receive HTTP 409.
- Throughput is intentionally limited.

These limitations are acceptable for the current deployment model.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Multiple concurrent browsers

Rejected.

Although technically possible, concurrent browser sessions introduce significantly more complexity:

- session isolation;
- download isolation;
- resource management;
- authentication consistency.

Current requirements do not justify this complexity.

---

## Request Queue

Rejected.

Queuing introduces additional infrastructure:

- worker processes;
- queue management;
- request persistence;
- timeout handling.

The expected workload is sufficiently low that rejecting concurrent requests is preferable.

---

## Multiple API Workers

Rejected.

The current lock exists in process memory.

Running multiple Uvicorn workers would allow simultaneous automations and invalidate the concurrency guarantee.

Production deployments should therefore use:

```
--workers 1
```

---

# Future Evolution

If future demand increases significantly, execution may evolve toward:

```
HTTP Request

↓

Queue

↓

Worker Pool

↓

Browser Pool

↓

External Platform
```

Such a redesign would require a different concurrency model and should be considered a new architectural decision.

---

# Rationale

The framework prioritizes reliability over maximum throughput.

Executing a single browser automation at a time greatly simplifies the implementation while providing predictable behaviour and avoiding race conditions in external platforms.

The chosen solution matches the expected production workload and preserves the existing architecture.

